++++++ Anouncement 1-20-2004 +++++

We have created an Official AW Path of Ascension Player's Guide.  It can be found in the PoA forum at the webpage noted below.  It is also available for download from our webpage.  It contains detailed explanations of all our rules, defines our area level restrictions, and offers some hints for new players on our areas and many of the terms players use here.

We have also updated and re-written some of the rules on this board to better reflect the current rule-set found in the player's guide and what our DM's are taught to enforce.  So READ THEM.

For information on our servers or gaming clan, or to get our Official Player's Guide go to http://ancientwarriors.org/forum/   

Registration is require to post in our forums, but not to read them.
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++


Warning: Playing this mod may result in addiction and loss of employment.
Path of Ascension is designed with teamplay in mind. Soloers will find it rough going.


General Rules:

Server Rules are enforced when and how the DM's choose.
Repeated violations can result in a wide range of actions, from jail time to permanent ban. The DM has a wide array of choices in between as well, including level loss, gold loss, item loss, xp loss, bannishment to hell, and more.

These rules are in no particular order:

Exploiters will not be tolerated. A large reward is in place for any who can provide information leading to the arrest and imprisonment, (or worse) of exploiters. An exploiter can be defined as someone who takes advantage of anything within the game for uses it was not intended. Example: Logging off and returning to prevent poison effects.

Battle Looters run the risk of the DM's attention. It is frowned upon, to say the least. Battle looters are defined as someone who constantly loots while others are in battle nearby. While the DM's may look the other way, if it becomes a problem or is excessive, the DM's may decide to become interested.

Town is off limits to combat.  The only time combat is permissible in town is if hostile monsters invade. (Even then, it is easy to injure a townperson, and be jailed or worse) The Town guard is well trained to handle such situations, but if you must enter the fray, do not use area effects. Absolutely no offensive action is to be directed at PC's or the Town NPC's.  This includes, but is not limited to, traps, spells, summoned creatures, pick pocketing, disarm, etc.

PvP Killing (Player vs Player Killing)

Players MAY NOT kill other players UNLESS they have DM permission AND the DM is currently on overseeing the kill.  No exceptions period.  If someone comes up and kills you, you may report it to a DM and ask for permission to seek your revenge.  If you decide to kill the other player before gaining permission we won't care who started it, but we will finish it.  Usually to the dismay of both players involved.

When a player kills another player, the victim loses xp and gold, while the killer gains. there are limits to this in place to prevent exploits, dont bother trying.


PARTYING & LEECHES

Leeching is frowned upon, and doesnt work well with this servers XP system, as you gain no experience if anyone in your nearby party is 5 or more levels higher than you. To gain more experience, party with several people near your level for the party bonus. Summoned creatures acualy contribute to xp, instead of reducing it, but do not count towards prty number.


THE UD (UnderDark)

The underworld is a very dangerous place.  Go there alone, or in a small group and you will most likely be killed.  Archemlis the Betrayer is not mercifull on stragglers.  Don't bother complaining...you have been warned. Its not that we discourage adventuring there.. in fact thats where some of the best loot is.  We just dont think anyone has any buisness going in there alone, without good backup.


PvP Stealing:  

To Thieves - We technically 'allow' PvP stealing on this mod.  However, would be thieves should know that we also don't like it, as by stealing from other players you are diminishing the gaming experience here for your victims.  Know also, that you steal at your own risk and that we have scripts which alert the DM's when a PvP theft occurs.  DM's may do anything they feel like when they see a message indicating a PvP theft, including but not limited to: ignoring it, informing the victim and given the victim permission to kill you, taking the item back, or in extreme cases (where the DM may feel the level of theft you are perpetuating is getting out of hand) teleport you to an area where NPC and monster thieves will have their way with you.  We tend to like poetic justice here.

To Victims of theft - You may NOT report or complain to the DM's or Admins regarding theft, as the vast majority of items lost are due to NPC or monster's stealing them or the item being disarmed and you forgetting to pick it up afterwards.  Since DM's are told when any PvP occurs via a script, and any retribution is up to the DM anyway, complaining or reporting thefts will be considered a waste of his time and they may decide to do something bad to you exibiting such disregard and for not following our rules.  REGARDLESS of who, how, or why a theft occurs, it does not give you the right to kill the thief.  ONLY the DM may give you permission to do so.


MISC

We encourage you to share your thoughts and ideas.  However, please do it on our forum and not to the DMs during the game. 
 
Talk to all NPC in town, and read the book in your inventory before asking questions that have probably already been answered.

Evil roleplayers: Your task is difficult here. Do not pick on lower level characters. Do not become homicidal. Have a reason for every evil act, and roleplay it. If what you are doing is ruining someone elses fun, whether you think it should or not, cease and desist immediately.  Keep the DM's as informed of your plans as possible, so that victims cannot make false claims.  If you do not follow these guidelines, prepare for a rough road as an evil character.

The little known vagrancy law:  The officers of Ascension do feel sympathy for the poor, and so they gladly give a night with a roof over your head if you are found begging in the streets. AKA "Jail"

Anyone caught resting for the sole purpose of creating spawns will be banned, no warning. If your rest is succesfull, move on.
Players who are inactive, and do not respond when questioned, may be booted to free up space for others, if space is needed. You may attempt to relog when you return to your keyboard. No offence is intended.

In addition to the rules of conduct, there are some things you need to know about PoA:
If you die, you will be forced to respawn in 2 minutes. If you want to prevent this, keep near people who have raise dead scrolls. (Like your party members)
If you respawn, you will lose xp, gold, and possibly an equipped item.
Some treasure chests spawn one item per party member in the area.
The spell elemental shield does not do damage to anyone, that effect has been replaced with regeneration.
When a container is opened, it disapears, and a loot bag is dropped. You can get your loot from the bag. This is part of the respawning container / trap script that is used here.
You can level your character to level 2 at the rowan tree in town.
Items left on ground will be despawned after a short time.
The server vault will be purged once per month... characters who have been inactive for 3 weeks will be deleted. This is necesary to reduce log in lag.
Characters are limited to 130 item types in inventory.Stacks of items, such as potions, are counted as 1 item per stack. When you exceed this limit, you will be sent to a small area,and you will not leave the area untill you are under the limit.This prevents hoarding, and server lag on logins.

As long as you follow the rules of conduct, you will most likely have a pleasant experience here.  Usualy, DM's are even willing to discuss transgressions, providing they do not have to deal with an attitude problem while trying to reason with a player.  Frequent abuse of the rules of conduct can and WILL result in a permanent ban, no appeals.  Giving a DM a hard time is probably a faster method of getting yourself banned.  If a DM asks you to do something, or stop doing something, telling the DM to "Go to hell" (or something along those lines) will most likely end up in YOU being sent to hell.

Thanks for reading, have fun :)

************ UPDATED 2019-05-06 ************
Following is a list of areas found in the game and the maximum level of character which should be looting or using that area.

NR = No restriction 
PO = Plot Only (items such as Mutant Fire Beetle Belly or to access areas such as the Deep Pit) 

The number in brackets represent the highest level that is appropriate. 

Abandoned mansion [16]
Ancient Crypt [6] 
Anduin Ruins [14 or PO] 
Ascension Sewer [12 or PO] 
Bandit Camp [8] 
Beetle Caves [6 or PO] 
Boat Ramp [8] 
BugBear Caves [12] 
Cesspool Dragon [16] 
Dread Caves [12] 
Duerger Mines [18] 
Eternal Dragons [NR] 
Forgotten Forest [12 or PO] 
Giants Lair [16] 
Gloomy Wood [16 or PO] 
Goblin Camp [7] 
Golem Sanctuary [12] 
Halls of Horror[18] 
Hobgoblin Mines [7] 
Krensher's Lair [7] 
Kobold Glade [7] 
Lava Pit [16] 
Lokis Hall [NR] 
Minotaur Den [16] 
Nether Caves [7] 
Ogre Cavern [12] 
Orc Warren [7] 
Promethius Pass [16 or PO] 
Rakshasha Coven [18] 
Swamp of Decay [12] 
Shadow Forest [7] 
Tainted Desert [NR] 
Tainted Hills [NR] 
Umber Maze [16] 


NOTES: 


Players please NOTE: There are exceptions - for example, if you are using a lower level area as a transition to get from town to a higher level area (for example: going through Ruins of Anduin to get to Tainted hills, or working on a quest), however it is important that you interact as little as possible with the environment during this journey (for example: grabbing treasure as you run past 'lower level' areas, or even fighting monsters other than those directly in your way may very well result in your immediate DM-assisted death). 

There may also be times when members of your party fall into the level restrictions but you are above them (for example: a lvl 18 in a party with lvl 14's in umbers). In these situations be careful, for if a DM sees such a group having too easy a tiime, he/she may decided to intervene. Thus, the previous example IS NOT a valid excuse in 100% of all cases. Use discretion, and be aware of how you are doing. If things are too easy, think about going somewhere with more of a challenge. 

For LOW LEVEL areas DMs will like factor in a characters class when applying these rules. Weaker classes will get the benefit of the doubt. But keep in mind this does not apply to mid or high level characters. Example: level 18-20 mage looting in the Ruins of Anduin. 

Also be aware that the DM's will take action against anyone who is, or appears to be, acting outside of the rules as stated above. Additionally, level 20 characters should not be joining parties going into areas they are not allowed (like going into Duergar or Rakasha with 16s and 17s). Those mid levels should be going with the level 20s to harder areas instead. 

Lastly, use common sense. If the challenge rating of the monster/npc you face is "effortless", or "easy" and you can kill everything in an area without difficulty, it is definately time to find harder challenges. If you don't, then don't complain if a DM suddenly makes the area MUCH more dangerous or an act of divine wrath shuffles you loose from the mortal coil on the spot. 

You have been warned.

Welcome to PoA

If you need any help ask the other players as most of them are very helpful.

Dont forget to checkout the server discord for information on runs and updates.
